# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hazelcast-imdg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast is a distributed computation and storage platform for consistent low-latency querying, aggregation, and stateful computation against event streams and traditional data sources.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] This guide outlines how Hazelcast works under the hood to help you understand some important concepts.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] In Hazelcast, data is load-balanced in-memory across a cluster.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] This cluster is a network of members, each of which runs Hazelcast.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] A cluster of Hazelcast members share both the data storage and computational load which can dynamically scale up and down.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When you add new members to the cluster, both the data and computations are automatically rebalanced across the cluster.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Members discover each other automatically and form a cluster. after the cluster is formed, members communicate with each other via TCP.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast supports automatic discovery in cloud environments such as Amazon EC2, Google Cloud Platform and Azure.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] You can also configure Hazelcast to discover members by TCP/IP or multicast.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] In addition, you can make use of the automatic member discovery in the Kubernetes environment.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast distributes your storage data, computational data, and backups, among all cluster members.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] This way, if a member is lost, Hazelcast can restore the data from these backups, providing continuous availability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Backups are distributed and stored in memory (RAM).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] The distribution happens on the partition level, where the primary data and its backups are stored in the partitions.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When a member in your cluster is lost, Hazelcast redistributes the backups on the remaining members so that every partition has a backup.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] This makes Hazelcast resilient to data loss.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Based on the configuration, data can be kept in multiple replicas of a partition.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] In Hazelcast, cluster members monitor the health of each other.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When a cluster member becomes inaccessible due to an event such as a network failure, other members cooperatively diagnose the state and immediately take over the responsibility of the failed member.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] To determine if a member is unreachable or crashed, Hazelcast provides built-in failure detectors.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast also provides replication over WAN for high availability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] You can have deployments across multiple data centers using the WAN replication mechanism which offers protection against a data center or wider network failures.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast as an AP system delivers availability and partition tolerance at the expense of consistency.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When a communication breakdown occurs, all members remain available, however some members affected by the partition might return an older version of data than others.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When the partition is resolved, Hazelcast typically synchronizes the members to repair all inconsistencies in the system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] As a CP system, Hazelcast delivers consistency and partition tolerance at the expense of availability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] When a partition occurs between any members, Hazelcast makes the non-consistent member unavailable until the partition is resolved.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Data structures exposed under `HazelcastInstance` API are all AP data structures and the ones accessed via `HazelcastInstance.getCPSubsystem()` provides CP structures and APIs, which are built on the Raft consensus algorithm.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] See the Consistency and Replication Model section and CP Subsystem section.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] The storage engine provides caching and data processing on top of Hazelcast’s key/value store called IMap.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] You can load and store cached data from/to external systems, control the eviction of data entries and execute your codes on them, use Hazelcast’s specification-compliant JCache implementation and integrate your cache with Spring.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] The Jet engine is responsible for running streaming applications.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] For this, it uses many different connectors (sources and sinks) to ingest data into Hazelcast and output data that data, and stateless/stateful transforms with operators including join, aggregate and sort to process data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] A data pipeline is a series of processing steps that consist of a source, one or more processing steps, and a sink.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] It may enable the flow of data from an application to a data warehouse, from a data lake to an analytics database, or into a payment processing system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast allows you to create data pipelines, using either SQL or the Hazelcast Java API.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast offers distributed implementations of standard collections, concurrency utilities, and publish/subscribe messaging model.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Standard collection implementations include Maps, Queues, Lists, Sets and Ringbuffers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Concurrency utilities include AtomicLongs, AtomicReferences, Semaphores and CountDownLatches.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] It also provides a broadcast messaging system based on publish/subscribe model; it lets applications communicate in real time at high speed.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Your applications can publish to specific channels called topics, and then one or more subscribers can read the messages from those topics.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast also provides the CP Subsystem for distributed coordination use cases such as leader election, distributed locking, synchronization and metadata management.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast’s SQL service lets you query static and streaming data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] You can load static data from sources (files and maps) to transform and analyze it.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Hazelcast can also load and query real-time streaming data as it is being generated, which is ideal for use cases that require complex queries with low latency, e.g., fraud detection.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/architecture] Besides performing transformations and queries, you can store your transform/query results in one or more systems; it is useful for sending results to other systems or caching results in Hazelcast to avoid running redundant queries.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] A **data grid** is an architecture or set of services that allows users to access, modify and transfer extremely large amounts of geographically distributed data for research purposes.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Data grids make this possible through a host of middleware applications and services that pull together data and resources from multiple administrative domains and then present it to users upon request.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data in a data grid can be located at a single site or multiple sites where each site can be its own administrative domain governed by a set of security restrictions as to who may access the data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Likewise, multiple replicas of the data may be distributed throughout the grid outside their original administrative domain and the security restrictions placed on the original data for who may access it must be equally applied to the replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Specifically developed data grid middleware is what handles the integration between users and the data they request by controlling access while making it available as efficiently as possible.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Middleware provides all the services and applications necessary for efficient management of datasets and files within the data grid while providing users quick access to the datasets and files.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There is a number of concepts and tools that must be available to make a data grid operationally viable.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] However, at the same time not all data grids require the same capabilities and services because of differences in access requirements, security and location of resources in comparison to users.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In any case, most data grids will have similar middleware services that provide for a universal name space, data transport service, data access service, data replication and resource management service.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] When taken together, they are key to the data grids functional capabilities.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] A universal or unified name space makes it possible to create logical file names (LFNs) that can be referenced within the data grid that map to PFNs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] When an LFN is requested or queried, all matching PFNs are returned to include possible replicas of the requested data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The end user can then choose from the returned results the most appropriate replica to use.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] This service is usually provided as part of a management system known as a Storage Resource Broker (SRB).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Information about the locations of files and mappings between the LFNs and PFNs may be stored in a metadata or replica catalogue.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The replica catalogue would contain information about LFNs that map to multiple replica PFNs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Another middleware service is that of providing for data transport or data transfer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Data transport will encompass multiple functions that are not just limited to the transfer of bits, to include such items as fault tolerance and data access.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Fault tolerance can be achieved in a data grid by providing mechanisms that ensures data transfer will resume after each interruption until all requested data is received.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There are multiple possible methods that might be used to include starting the entire transmission over from the beginning of the data to resuming from where the transfer was interrupted.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] As an example, GridFTP provides for fault tolerance by sending data from the last acknowledged byte without starting the entire transfer from the beginning.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data transport service also provides for the low-level access and connections between hosts for file transfer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data transport service might optionally include a network overlay function to facilitate the routing and transfer of data as well as file I/O functions that allow users to see remote files as if they were local to their system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data transport service hides the complexity of access and transfer between the different systems to the user so it appears as one unified data source.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Data access services work hand in hand with the data transfer service to provide security, access controls and management of any data transfers within the data grid.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Security services provide mechanisms for authentication of users to ensure they are properly identified.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Common forms of security for authentication can include the use of passwords or Kerberos (protocol).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Authorization services are the mechanisms that control what the user is able to access after being identified through authentication.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Common forms of authorization mechanisms can be as simple as file permissions.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] However, need for more stringent controlled access to data is done using Access Control Lists (ACLs), Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and Tasked-Based Authorization Controls (TBAC).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] These types of controls can be used to provide granular access to files to include limits on access times, duration of access to granular controls that determine which files can be read or written to.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The final data access service that might be present to protect the confidentiality of the data transport is encryption.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The most common form of encryption for this task has been the use of SSL while in transport.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] While all of these access services operate within the data grid, access services within the various administrative domains that host the datasets will still stay in place to enforce access rules.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data grid access services must be in step with the administrative domains access services for this to work.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] To meet the needs for scalability, fast access and user collaboration, most data grids support replication of datasets to points within the distributed storage architecture.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The use of replicas allows multiple users faster access to datasets and the preservation of bandwidth since replicas can often be placed strategically close to or within sites where users need them.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] However, replication of datasets and creation of replicas is bound by the availability of storage within sites and bandwidth between sites.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The replication and creation of replica datasets is controlled by a replica management system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The replica management system determines user needs for replicas based on input requests and creates them based on availability of storage and bandwidth.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] All replicas are then cataloged or added to a directory based on the data grid as to their location for query by users.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In order to perform the tasks undertaken by the replica management system, it needs to be able to manage the underlying storage infrastructure.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data management system will also ensure the timely updates of changes to replicas are propagated to all nodes.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There are a number of ways the replication management system can handle the updates of replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The updates may be designed around a centralized model where a single master replica updates all others, or a decentralized model, where all peers update each other.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The topology of node placement may also influence the updates of replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] If a hierarchy topology is used then updates would flow in a tree like structure through specific paths.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In a flat topology it is entirely a matter of the peer relationships between nodes as to how updates take place.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In a hybrid topology consisting of both flat and hierarchy topologies updates may take place through specific paths and between peers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There are a number of ways the replication management system can handle the creation and placement of replicas to best serve the user community.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] If the storage architecture supports replica placement with sufficient site storage, then it becomes a matter of the needs of the users who access the datasets and a strategy for placement of replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There have been numerous strategies proposed and tested on how to best manage replica placement of datasets within the data grid to meet user requirements.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] There is not one universal strategy that fits every requirement the best.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] It is a matter of the type of data grid and user community requirements for access that will determine the best strategy to use.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Replicas can even be created where the files are encrypted for confidentiality that would be useful in a research project dealing with medical files.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The following section contains several strategies for replica placement.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Dynamic replication is an approach to placement of replicas based on popularity of the data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The method has been designed around a hierarchical replication model.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data management system keeps track of available storage on all nodes.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] It also keeps track of requests (hits) for which data clients (users) in a site are requesting.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] When the number of hits for a specific dataset exceeds the replication threshold it triggers the creation of a replica on the server that directly services the user's client.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] If the direct servicing server known as a father does not have sufficient space, then the father's father in the hierarchy is then the target to receive a replica and so on up the chain until it is exhausted.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data management system algorithm also allows for the dynamic deletion of replicas that have a null access value or a value lower than the frequency of the data to be stored to free up space.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] This improves system performance in terms of response time, number of replicas and helps load balance across the data grid.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] This method can also use dynamic algorithms that determine whether the cost of creating the replica is truly worth the expected gains given the location.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] This method of replication like the one for dynamic replication has been designed around a hierarchical replication model found in most data grids.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] It works on a similar algorithm to dynamic replication with file access requests being a prime factor in determining which files should be replicated.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] A key difference, however, is the number and frequency of replica creations is keyed to a dynamic threshold that is computed based on request arrival rates from clients over a period of time.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] If the number of requests on average exceeds the previous threshold and shows an upward trend, and storage utilization rates indicate capacity to create more replicas, more replicas may be created.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] As with dynamic replication, the removal of replicas that have a lower threshold that were not created in the current replication interval can be removed to make space for the new replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Like the adaptive and dynamic replication methods before, fair-share replication is based on a hierarchical replication model.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Also, like the two before, the popularity of files play a key role in determining which files will be replicated.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The difference with this method is the placement of the replicas is based on access load and storage load of candidate servers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] A candidate server may have sufficient storage space but be servicing many clients for access to stored files.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Placing a replicate on this candidate could degrade performance for all clients accessing this candidate server.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Therefore, placement of replicas with this method is done by evaluating each candidate node for access load to find a suitable node for the placement of the replica.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] If all candidate nodes are equivalently rated for access load, none or less accessed than the other, then the candidate node with the lowest storage load will be chosen to host the replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Similar methods to the other described replication methods are used to remove unused or lower requested replicates if needed.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Replicas that are removed might be moved to a parent node for later reuse should they become popular again.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The above three replica strategies are but three of many possible replication strategies that may be used to place replicas within the data grid where they will improve performance and access.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Below are some others that have been proposed and tested along with the previously described replication strategies.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Such characteristics of the data grid systems as large scale and heterogeneity require specific methods of tasks scheduling and resource allocation.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] To resolve the problem, majority of systems use extended classic methods of scheduling.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Others invite fundamentally different methods based on incentives for autonomous nodes, like virtual money or reputation of a node.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Another specificity of data grids, dynamics, consists in the continuous process of connecting and disconnecting of nodes and local load imbalance during an execution of tasks.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] That can make obsolete or non-optimal results of initial resource allocation for a task.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] As a result, much of the data grids utilize execution-time adaptation techniques that permit the systems to reflect to the dynamic changes: balance the load, replace disconnecting nodes, use the profit of newly connected nodes, recover a task execution after faults.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The resource management system represents the core functionality of the data grid.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] It is the heart of the system that manages all actions related to storage resources.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In some data grids it may be necessary to create a federated RMS architecture because of different administrative policies and a diversity of possibilities found within the data grid in place of using a single RMS.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] In such a case the RMSs in the federation will employ an architecture that allows for interoperability based on an agreed upon set of protocols for actions related to storage resources.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Data grids have been designed with multiple topologies in mind to meet the needs of the scientific community.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] On the right are four diagrams of various topologies that have been used in data grids.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Each topology has a specific purpose in mind for where it will be best utilized.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Each of these topologies is further explained below.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The need for data grids was first recognized by the scientific community concerning climate modeling, where terabyte and petabyte sized data sets were becoming the norm for transport between sites.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] More recent research requirements for data grids have been driven by the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN, the Laser Interferometer Gravitational Wave Observatory (LIGO), and the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] These examples of scientific instruments produce large amounts of data that need to be accessible by large groups of geographically dispersed researchers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Other uses for data grids involve governments, hospitals, schools and businesses where efforts are taking place to improve services and reduce costs by providing access to dispersed and separate data systems through the use of data grids.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] From its earliest beginnings, the concept of a Data Grid to support the scientific community was thought of as a specialized extension of the “grid” which itself was first envisioned as a way to link super computers into meta-computers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] However, that was short lived and the grid evolved into meaning the ability to connect computers anywhere on the web to get access to any desired files and resources, similar to the way electricity is delivered over a grid by simply plugging in a device.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The device gets electricity through its connection and the connection is not limited to a specific outlet.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] From this the data grid was proposed as an integrating architecture that would be capable of delivering resources for distributed computations.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] It would also be able to service numerous to thousands of queries at the same time while delivering gigabytes to terabytes of data for each query.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data grid would include its own management infrastructure capable of managing all aspects of the data grids performance and operation across multiple wide area networks while working within the existing framework known as the web.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data grid has also been defined more recently in terms of usability; what must a data grid be able to do in order for it to be useful to the scientific community.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Proponents of this theory arrived at several criteria.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] One, users should be able to search and discover applicable resources within the data grid from amongst its many datasets.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Two, users should be able to locate datasets within the data grid that are most suitable for their requirement from amongst numerous replicas.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Three, users should be able to transfer and move large datasets between points in a short amount of time.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Four, the data grid should provide a means to manage multiple copies of datasets within the data grid.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] And finally, the data grid should provide security with user access controls within the data grid, i.e. which users are allowed to access which data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] The data grid is an evolving technology that continues to change and grow to meet the needs of an expanding community.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] One of the earliest programs begun to make data grids a reality was funded by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) in 1997 at the University of Chicago.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] This research spawned by DARPA has continued down the path to creating open source tools that make data grids possible.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] As new requirements for data grids emerge projects like the Globus Toolkit will emerge or expand to meet the gap.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/data-grid] Data grids along with the "Grid" will continue to evolve.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] In computing, a **distributed cache** is an extension of the traditional concept of cache used in a single locale.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] A distributed cache may span multiple servers so that it can grow in size and in transactional capacity.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] It is mainly used to store application data residing in database and web session data.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] The idea of distributed caching has become feasible now because main memory has become very cheap and network cards have become very fast, with 1 Gbit now standard everywhere and 10 Gbit gaining traction.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] Also, a distributed cache works well on lower cost machines usually employed for web servers as opposed to database servers which require expensive hardware.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] An emerging internet architecture known as Information-centric networking (ICN) is one of the best examples of a distributed cache network.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] The ICN is a network level solution hence the existing distributed network cache management schemes are not well suited for ICN.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] In the supercomputer environment, distributed cache is typically implemented in the form of burst buffer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-cache] In distributed caching, each cache key is assigned to a specific shard (a.k.a. partition).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Hazelcast offers distributed implementations of many common data structures.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] For each of the client languages, Hazelcast mimics as closely as possible the natural interface of the structure.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] For example in Java, the map follows `java.util.Map` semantics.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Hazelcast uses the name of a distributed object to determine in which partition it will be put.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Now, these two queues will be put into the same partition whose partition key is `foo`.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Note that you can use the `getPartitionKey()` method to learn the partition key of a distributed object.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Hazelcast offers a `get()` method for most of its distributed objects.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] To load an object, first create a Hazelcast instance and then use the related `get()` method on this instance.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] To destroy a Hazelcast distributed object, you can use the `destroy()` method, which clears and releases all resources of the object.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Therefore, you must use it with care since a reload with the same object reference after the object is destroyed creates a new data structure without an error.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] See the following example code where one of the queues are destroyed and the other one is accessed.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] As you see, no error is generated and a new queue resource is created.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Hazelcast is designed to create any distributed data structure whenever it is accessed.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Therefore, keep in mind that a data structure is recreated when you perform an operation on it even after you have destroyed it.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] As to the configuration of distributed objects, Hazelcast uses the default settings from the `hazelcast.xml` file that comes with your Hazelcast member download.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Of course, you can provide an explicit configuration in this file or programmatically according to your needs.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] See the Understanding Configuration section.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Note that, most of Hazelcast’s distributed objects are created lazily: A distributed object is created once the first operation accesses it.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] If you want to use an object you loaded in other places, you can safely reload it using its reference without creating a new Hazelcast instance.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] AP data structures prefer availability over consistency.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] When a partition occurs, all members remain available but some might return an older version of data than others.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] Here is an example of how you can retrieve existing AP data structure instances and how you can listen for instance events, such as an instance being created or destroyed.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] A CP data structure delivers consistency and partition tolerance at the expense of availability.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] When a partition occurs between any two CP members, the non-consistent CP member must halt until the partition is resolved.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/distributed-data-structures] To learn about CP members and how Hazelcast delivers consistency and partition tolerance, see CP Subsystem.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Welcome to the documentation for Hazelcast Platform, the leading in-memory data grid and compute platform for building real-time applications.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast Platform combines a fast data store and powerful stream processing into a single platform, eliminating latency moving data between databases and processing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast offers Enterprise Edition and Community Edition versions of Hazelcast Platform with a range of deployment options, including Docker and Kubernetes.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] You can get started with either version by following the quickstarts below.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast Enterprise Edition is a licensed product that extends the Community Edition to provide many additional features and benefits for production environments, including regular patch releases and a support subscription.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast is implemented in Java (with choice of embedded or client/server mode) and has clients for Java, C++, .NET, REST, Python, Go and Node.js.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast also speaks Memcache and REST protocols.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] The best way to get started and understand Hazelcast is to dive in and create a Hello World application.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] If you’re looking for more detailed information on what’s new and how to install or upgrade existing Hazelcast deployments, check out the sections below.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Find out how Hazelcast works under the hood, and learn how to deploy and build applications with Hazelcast.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Discover how to operate and manage your Hazelcast clusters effectively.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Learn how to integrate Hazelcast with various frameworks and tools.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast-latest] Hazelcast also provides tools for managing your Hazelcast clusters and Kubernetes/Openshift deployments.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] In computing, **Hazelcast** is a unified real-time data platform implemented in Java that combines a fast data store with stream processing.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] It is also the name of the company that develops the product.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] The Hazelcast company is funded by venture capital and headquartered in Palo Alto, California.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] In a Hazelcast grid, data is evenly distributed among the nodes of a computer cluster, allowing for horizontal scaling of processing and available storage.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] Backups are also distributed among nodes to protect against failure of any single node.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] Hazelcast can run on-premises, in the cloud (Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Cloud Foundry, OpenShift), virtually (VMware), and in Docker containers.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] The Hazelcast Cloud Discovery Service Provider Interface (SPI) enables cloud-based or on-premises nodes to auto-discover each other.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] The Hazelcast platform can manage memory for many types of applications.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] It offers an Open Binary Client Protocol to support APIs for any binary programming language.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] The Hazelcast and open-source community members have created client APIs for programming languages that include Java, .NET, C++, Python, Node.js and Go.
[src:hazelcast-imdg/hazelcast] Hazelcast is also used in academia and research as a framework for distributed execution and storage.
